            <abstract id="ref3" label="Abstract">The Teachers Action Caucus, founded in 1968 as Teachers for Community Control, was a rank and file opposition group within the United Federation of Teachers (New York City) that was founded by former members of the radical Teachers' Union of the City of New York (1916-1964), many of whose leading activists were Communists, and by younger teachers representing the New Left of the 1960s. The records contain agendas, circulars, clippings, correspondence, fliers, minutes, newsletters, and petitions documenting the Caucus' campaigns for union offices, for union democracy and improved working conditions, for community participation in the administration of the school system, and in opposition to the domestic and foreign policy positions taken by the leadership of the United Federation of Teachers and its president, Albert Shanker.</abstract>
